In an immunosensor the core-cover interface of an optical waveguide structure is coated with a chemo-optical transducer receptor layer, which can selectively bind to specific analyte molecules present in the cover medium. The receptor-analyte reaction obeys the law of mass action, which states that the rate of a reaction is proportional to the concentration of the reactants. At equilibrium, the rate of formation of the receptor-analyte complex is equal to the rate of breaking, and the equilibrium constant, K, can be written as(10.11)\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
